<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Survey of Nordic Banking and Finance (7): Time may be right
for freedom - Karen Fossli sees signs of recovery among Norway's commercial
banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORWAY'S ailing commercial bank sector has at last begun to show signs of
recovery, to judge by this year's first-quarter results. The improvement has
persuaded the government that the time may be right to embark on a
reprivatisation programme. The first target next year is likely to be the
Christiania Bank (CBK), the country's second biggest, in which the state
owns about 98.8 per cent of the share capital.
The state also controls about 70 per cent of the share capital of Den norske
Bank, the country's biggest commercial bank, while Fokus Bank, the third
biggest commercial bank, is wholly state-owned. More than NKr27bn has been
pumped into the bank sector over the past five years through state-backed
bank guarantee and investment funds and by the banks' own guarantee funds.
Financial deregulation is at the heart of the banking crisis. It fuelled
competition but led to less-than-prudent domestic and foreign expansion.
After Norway's oil-dependent economy plunged into recession in 1986 world
crude oil prices fell to below Dollars 6 a barrel. This culminated in the
banks' collapse nearly two years ago
According to London-based Davis International Banking Consultants, appointed
by the government earlier this year to study capacity in the domestic
banking sector, annual lending growth by commercial and savings banks -
which had been running at about 15 per cent in the early 1980s - shot up to
about 30 per cent between 1984 and 1988.
Between 1980 and 1989 the commercial banks' loan-deposit ratio to non-bank
sectors nearly doubled from 86 to more than 150 per cent, making them
dangerously dependent on wholesale and international deposits. The ratio
fell to about 122 per cent by the end of 1992 and to 116 per cent in this
year's first quarter.
For the savings banks, the non-bank loan/liability ratio rose from 72 to 117
per cent before declining to 111 per cent by the end of last year. In the
first quarter of this year, there was a 2.5 per cent rise in the loan volume
of the savings banks, at the expense of the commercial banks.
The biggest savings bank, Sparebanken Nor, which is also the third biggest
bank in Norway, is moving aggressively to boost its share of the corporate
lending market. DIBC estimates these four banks have a total of 100,000
corporate clients, about 40 per cent of the 240,000 companies in Norway.
Households contribute 75 per cent of funds available to financial
institutions and account for 60 per cent of overall loans. The commercial
banks have only about 30 per cent of retail deposits (compared with 60 per
cent of corporate deposits) and 25 per cent of retail loans.
With the onset of recession the banks found themselves holding bulging,
non-performing loan portfolios. To make matters worse property, which serves
as collateral for loans, plunged in value by an estimated 30 per cent.
There are recent signs that property values have bottomed out and may even
be on the upturn in some parts of Norway. Credit losses were more than
halved to NKr8.7bn last year from a peak of NKr22bn in 1991.
In the first quarter of 1993 CBK returned a net profit of NKr209m, against a
loss of NKr86m in the same period last year while DnB cut net losses to
NKr138m from NKr601m. Fokus Bank achieved a first quarter net profit of
NKr36.7m, against a net loss of NKr137.6m.
The improvement was due primarily to gains in shares and bonds, and to
foreign currency gains. The banks were also granted subsidised loans by the
central bank and ordered by the state to reduce their balance sheets and cut
costs. They were helped by 12 cuts in the central bank's key overnight
lending rate, currently 7.5 per cent.
DIBC believes that by the end of this year Norway will have the lowest
branch density among its Nordic peers and the lowest number of bank staff
per inhabitants. The Association of Bank Employees estimates that some
10,000 jobs in the sector have been lost in the past five years, but that
may not be the end. Both CBK and DnB warn that the high level of
non-performing loans makes it far too early to call an end to the six-year
banking crisis. There is growing concern about declining loan volume owing
to a prolonged lack of corporate interest in investing in Norway.
As the commercial banks struggle to regain profitability - there is a target
return on equity of 15 to 20 per cent - they are meeting increasing
competition from the savings banks and mortgage companies which have been
transformed into banks.
They can take some comfort from DIBC's prediction that when the European
Economic Area is implemented later this year - to give banks from other
European Free Trade Association countries and the European Community the
right to open branches in Norway - there will be no immediate impact on the
retail market. In fact, foreign banks have shown little interest in
expanding to Norway and recently a couple of foreign banks closed up shop.
However, DIBC forecasts that with little or no net growth in revenue, it
will be necessary to make continuing cuts in branch and staff numbers to pay
salary increases and achieve adequate levels of profits. 'The capacity
needed for retail banking is likely to decrease by 2-3 per cent per annum
for the foreseeable future,' it says.
DIBC warns that the authorities could damage the banking system - and
therefore the economy as a whole - by insisting on substantial cuts in
capacity, particularly at commercial banks, as a short-term response to the
banking crisis. 'Such a knee-jerk reaction may not be justified in relation
to the banks' long-term prospects.'
In Tokyo earlier this year, Mr Sigbjoern Johnsen, finance minister, told
Japanese bankers that structural adjustments would be necessary to
strengthen the financial sector. 'In our view there is still excess capacity
in the banking sector,' he said. Later this year, Mr Johnsen is due to
announce measures to curb capacity.
</TEXT>
