<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Mirror faces Pounds 6m claim for rent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MIRROR GROUP Newspapers will be in default by Pounds 6m on the rent of its
London headquarters at the end of this month, as a decision looms on the
group's new location.
Mr Maurice Withall, the receiver to Robert Maxwell Estates, MGN's landlord,
at accountants Grant Thornton, confirmed yesterday that MGN would be
delinquent for the third successive quarter if it did not pay rent at the
end of June.
Robert Maxwell Estates, which was part of the private Maxwell business
empire, is the landlord to the Holborn site in central London, and the
immediate tenant on the property is Maxwell Communication Corporation. But
because MCC is in administration under English insolvency law, Mr Withall
has taken legal action to pursue MGN, the sub-tenant, for payment.
MGN relented after originally refusing to pay rent from the point at which
the Maxwell empire collapsed in late 1991. It stopped paying rent again from
the quarter ending last December. It argues that it should be able to offset
the payments against money from MCC, which has not been provided. Mr Withall
is suing MGN for the outstanding amounts. He has offered the company a
settlement as part of negotiations for the sale of the site to the newspaper
group.
</TEXT>
