<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Smith may get second reform chance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVEN IF Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, loses his fight at this year's
Labour Party conference to establish a new relationship between the party
and the unions he may have another chance next year, party officials say.
Labour's organisation committee will recommend to the party's national
executive next week that the most contentious issue between Mr Smith and the
unions - the establishment of a new system for selecting parliamentary
candidates - be postponed until the work of the Boundaries Commission is
complete next year.
That means that even if Mr Smith's support for removing the unions from the
selection procedure and introducing a system of 'one-member-one-vote' fails
at the conference this September, the issue can still be won next year
without causing havoc with selections procedures.
There is a strong chance that the executive will accept the organisation
committee recommendation. Some opponents of the Smith reform plan see the
move as an attempt by his supporters to create an opportunity to change the
rules next year.
But the Smith camp insists it is not interested in delay and can still win
the vote on the introduction of one-member-one-vote for the selection of
parliamentary candidates at this year's conference.
With most of the unions committed by their conference decisions to retain
the block vote, however, a Smith victory probably depends on a few big
unions abstaining.
</TEXT>
