<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Survey warns on Midland projects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WEST MIDLANDS planners have been told there is no need for a further large
out-of-town shopping centre. They have been told that such a centre would
jeopardise investment elsewhere in the Birmingham-Black Country conurbation.
These recommendations are contained in a study assessing the impact on the
region of the Merry Hill shopping centre in Dudley by the consultants Roger
Tym and Partners and Colquhoun Transportation Planning.
The study, to be published soon, was commissioned by the region's local
authorities, Centro, their public transport arm, the environment department
and Marks and Spencer.
Taken with the running dispute about the legality of the planning permission
granted for a big retail development at Trafford, Manchester, the study's
findings fuel the arguments about the merits of large out-of-town shopping
centres when government economic and social policy is directed at inner city
regeneration.
Merry Hill, with 260 shops on 1.39m sq ft of retail floorspace, is the
second largest shopping centre in Europe, exceeded only by MetroCentre in
Gateshead. It was created by Richardson Developments on the site of an old
steelworks, bought by Mountleigh in 1990 and, after Mountleigh called in the
receivers, bought for Pounds 128m by Chelsfield last February.
The Roger Tym study found that Merry Hill gained market share between 1989
and 1993. 'By far the biggest loss was at Dudley, whose 1993 market share is
less than one third of the 1989 level,' it says. Stourbridge, West Bromwich
and Kidderminister also suffered significant falls in market share.
Mr Bill Brisbane, who worked on the study, noted that the Merry Hill impact
was not unique. MetroCentre had hurt Gateshead, and Meadowhall outside
Sheffield had hurt the town centre in the same way as Merry Hill had hurt
Dudley. Anecdotal evidence suggested that the Lakeside centre at Thurrock
was having a similar effect on Grays, Essex.
Mr Brisbane suggested that although Merry Hill had created 3,370 jobs - 69
per cent of them part-time - to replace those lost by the closure of the
steelworks and had drawn shoppers and hence funds into the region, it was
not yet possible to say that out-of-town shopping centres had 'a positive
net benefit' on the region in which they were situated.
In the case of the West Midlands, the study concludes that, as there is
unlikely to be significant population growth and 'in the short-term it is
improbable that there will be substantial growth in consumer expenditure',
there is little clear need for another centre such as Merry Hill.
</TEXT>
