<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Standards organisation finds itself on trial: The
resignation of its chief executive and impending government scrutiny signal
a shake-up for the BSI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE space of two weeks the British Standards Institution, which writes
standards for industry, has lost its chief executive after a boardroom row
and the government has ordered a review of the institution and its
activities.
BSI says the two events were unconnected. But for an organisation with a
profile low to the point of invisibility, this sudden flurry of activity
suggests that something is amiss.
As well as having a monopoly in co-ordinating the writing of standards, BSI
carries out product testing and certification in competition with dozens of
independent laboratories and commercial certification companies.
The combination of these activities  - BSI's German and French counterparts
are responsible only for writing standards  - has turned BSI into a large
and profitable business. It made an operating surplus of Pounds 7.5m last
year on turnover of Pounds 74m and employs more than 2,000 people. Its new
quality assurance standard, BS5750, adopted by about 20,000 British
bussineses, has proved a money-spinner, contributing nearly half of turnover
and two thirds of the surplus.
There has been growing controversy over BS5750, however. Small businesses in
particular say it is bureaucratic and inappropriate to their needs. They
have forced BSI to set up a committee to review the issue.
Meanwhile, there is increasing demand for Europe-wide standards. Countries
which take the lead in writing European and international standards  - the
UK, Germany and France each account for more than 20 per cent of
international standards  - can gain considerable competitive advantage.
Highly profitable though it is, BSI's transformation from a quasi Civil
Service bureaucracy into a commercial organisation has been recent and has
involved considerable  - as yet unfinished  - changes.
Mr Michael Sanderson, formerly managing director of AWD Bedford Trucks, was
brought in as BSI's first chief executive 18 months ago to spearhead its
modernisation and 'lead a major programme of cultural change'. BSI's
cumbersome committee structure was simplified to speed decision making.
Mr Sanderson resigned on June 1 over what the company called 'a deep
disagreement with the board on important matters of policy and management'.
Neither side would comment further, although there is a suspicion among
industry observers that Mr Sanderson was not pushing change at a fast enough
rate.
Barely had Mr Sanderson cleared his desk when Mr Michael Heseltine, trade
and industry secretary, announced a government review of BSI, its funding
and the issue of standards writing. He has called into question whether such
a profitable organisation needs the Pounds 4.5m annual government subsidy it
receives, whether the standards it writes are of sufficiently high quality
and how industry's input should be organised.
The government estimates that industry's contribution to standards writing
amounts to Pounds 200m in the form of expert time provided to the standards
drafting committees.
The government wants to know if standards contribute to the competitiveness
of British industry and what BSI's role should be now that European and
international standards are becoming more important than national standards.
Mr Derek Prior, communications manager, said BSI received much less
government support than its Continental counterparts and 'could produce a
plan for survival without a government grant.'
He dismissed the suggestion that the move to European and international
standards could threaten BSI  - instead it increased the need for strong
national standards bodies to represent national interests, he said.
BSI may have survived previous official reviews unscathed, but the present
government is committed to privatisation and to saving money where it can,
and BSI's mounting profitability may increase its chances of being
privatised.
</TEXT>
<XX>
