<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Bosses adopt more green policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S boardrooms are devoting an increasing amount of time to
environmental issues, although they are still given relatively low priority
in many businesses.
A survey conducted among 325 UK companies on behalf of the Institute of
Directors shows that, in spite of the recession, directors are paying more
attention to the impact which their businesses have on the environment.
Nearly one third say they have adopted a formal corporate environmental
policy but the report also concludes that most continue to address the issue
'as a threat and not as an opportunity'.
A rising number of directors acknowledge that environmental considerations
are being driven primarily by the need for compliance, rather than by
broader social considerations.
Nearly three quarters have yet to operate any form of environmental audit
and only 1 per cent of businesses have a manager with specific
responsibility for environmental issues. In most companies the managing
director is still held to be responsible. The survey shows that 65 per cent
of company directors say the environment featured on their board's agenda
last year, up from 53 per cent the previous year.
Predictably, companies in construction, mining and manufacturing regularly
featured the environment on the board's agenda, while service and
distribution operations were less concerned.
But the survey also shows that few companies spend more than 10 per cent of
boardroom time on environmental questions. Nearly half the companies
surveyed reported that they were undertaking investment to meet
environmental obligations. More than one third said action was being taken
in response to laws either planned or already imposed by the UK and EC,
while the balance cited social responsibility, 'corporate citizenship' or
market forces as the impetus.
Only 6 per cent of the directors questioned rated themselves very
knowledgeable about their companies' legal environmental responsibilities,
and 44 per cent thought they were quite well informed.
</TEXT>
