<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Mortgage arrears leap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of homeowners in the UK more than six months in arrears with
their mortgage payments has risen by a quarter, the most extensive and
up-to-date survey of mortgage debt shows.
The survey, published today in Roof magazine, shows that 360,100 households
were six or more months behind with their mortgage payments at the end of
March, up from 290,080 last year. The number in short-term debt is
continuing to fall but one in 12 homeowners is two or more months in arrears
with mortgage payments. In spite of the halving of interest rates since 1991
the total in arrears of two months or more rose by 27,000 in the year to the
end of March, bringing the total to 800,150.
The survey, carried out annually by Ms Janet Ford of Loughborough
University, draws on data from 41 lenders of all types, responsible for 60
per cent of UK loans. It covers more lenders than the figures released
periodically by the Council of Mortgage Lenders, which do not include
short-term arrears.
The figures highlight the trend in arrears from short-term to long-term
debt. The number of households two months in arrears is at its lowest for
four years. Arrears of more than a year have jumped by more than 50 per cent
to 156,740.
The growth in the number of homeowners more than a year in arrears reflects
the success of the government in persuading lenders not to repossess such
homes. Until the launch of the mortgage rescue package at the end of 1991
lenders normally repossessed homes when arrears exceeded six months. One
element in the package was the direct payment to lenders of the part of
social security benefits meant to cover mortgage interest. But only 17 per
cent of those covered by the direct payment of mortgage interest are in
arrears, according to the survey.
The vast majority of those in arrears do not qualify for means-tested
benefits. About four fifths of those in arrears are outside the social
security safety net, and are typically people in low-wage employment or
families where only one partner is unemployed.
The survey says that the number of homes repossessed in the year to March
was 60,500. This compares with the CML figure of 68,540 for last year and
suggests that repossessions in the first quarter have fallen to almost half
the level of the first quarter of last year.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                       HOMEOWNERS IN ARREARS
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Period in arrears             March 31 1993      March 31 1992
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
2 months                         198,000             207,780
3-5 months                       242,050             275,380
6-11 months                      203,360             186,200
12 or more months                156,740             103,880
Total arrears                    800,150             773,240
Number of mortgages            9,920,000           9,800,000
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Roof Magazine
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
