<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Bosnia leader to be pressed on settlement: Owen sees five
autonomous provinces within existing state
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC FOREIGN ministers will hold talks with Bosnia's Moslem president, Mr Alia
Izetbegovic, in Copenhagen today as pressure mounts on the Moslems to accept
Serb and Croat territorial gains in the war-ravaged republic.
The talks  - which coincide with the opening-day of the EC summit  - come as
the Community strives to salvage something from the wreckage of the
Vance-Owen plan for a Bosnian peace settlement.
Mr Izetbegovic, who asked for the meeting with EC ministers, has opposed
recent Serb and Croat proposals for dividing Bosnia on ethnic lines.
At an emergency meeting of EC foreign ministers last night, several EC
delegations voiced objections to any EC move towards partition of Bosnia.
But after the tense discussions, Lord Owen, the EC peace mediator, and Mr
Niels Helvig Petersen, Denmark's foreign minister, made clear that time was
running out for the Bosnian Moslems to reach a political settlement.
Lord Owen said he expected new guidelines for land-swaps between the Croats,
Serbs and Bosnian Moslems to be issued this week by EC leaders and Mr
Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary-general. He would put these to the
presidents of Serbia and Croatia.
Lord Owen acknowledged that these guidelines would be less generous to the
Moslems than those under the Vance-Owen plan, which he drew up along with
the former UN mediator, Mr Cyrus Vance. But he said the best the EC could do
was to try to help Mr Izetbegovic by threatening economic sanctions against
Croatia and tougher economic pressure on Serbia.
Lord Owen presented foreign ministers with an outline map which provided for
five autonomous provinces within the existing Bosnian state. The plan, which
provides for some Serb withdrawals, would involve the creation of two Croat,
two Moslem and one Serb province.
The Moslems would need guaranteed access to the Adriatic and to the River
Danube.
Lord Owen said that conditions inside Bosnia were so desperate for the
civilian population that there had to be a negotiated settlement. But he
added: 'There has to be roll-back (of territorial gains).'
Senior British officials cautioned that this plan would have to be agreed by
all parties and was still in its early stages.
Mr Vance, now in the US, described recent peace moves as a 'tragic mistake'
that would 'end up rewarding those involved in ethnic cleansing'.
</TEXT>
