<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Serbs set Krajina on course for union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
REBEL Serb leaders from Croatia said yesterday that their weekend referendum
on the union of their self-styled state with other Serb-held territory was
the 'final act' towards the creation of a new Serb state.
Elsewhere, Sarajevo radio reported fierce fighting between Croat and mainly
Moslem Bosnian troops in four towns in central Bosnia as United Nations
commanders played down the threat by a Moslem commander in Tuzla, the
north-eastern industrial city, to unleash toxic chlorine to 'neutralise all
living forces in almost all Europe'.
Local officials of the Republic of Serbian Krajina (RSK), Serb-held
territory which covers about a third of Croatia, yesterday confirmed a high
turnout for the two-day poll.
The overwhelming majority was expected to vote Yes on union with Srpska
Republika, the self-proclaimed Serb state in Bosnia, with the option to
unite later with Serbia and Montenegro, the remaining members of Yugoslavia.
The RSK comprises three enclaves of Croatian territory seized by rebel Serbs
during Croatia's 1991 war of independence from former Yugoslavia.
Mr Milan Babic, the mayor of Knin, the stronghold of the RSK, said: 'This is
the final act of carrying out the people's will. The rest is up to the
politicians.' The referendum was held amid warnings by Serb leaders that
Croatia would cross UN lines to prevent the vote. Mr Nikica Valentic,
Croatian prime minister, said Zagreb would not intervene to stop the
referendum, and called for a diplomatic solution to the Krajina question.
Meanwhile, a 10-lorry UN convoy carrying food and medicine yesterday headed
for Gorazde, one of six UN-designated safe areas, and the UN resumed its
humanitarian airlift to Sarajevo.
Mr Milan Panic, former Yugoslav prime minister, arrived in Belgrade
yesterday to meet Serbian opposition leaders, aides said, Reuter reports
from Belgrade. His return on a visit from the US coincides with an outcry in
Serbia and abroad over the police beating and arrest of Mr Vuk Draskovic,
opposition leader. Mr Panic is seen in Serbia as the only serious contender
for power against President Slobodan Milosevic.
