</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Lombard League wins Milan race
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE populist Lombard League last night confirmed its hold on the voters of
northern Italy by winning the mayoral election for Milan.
The run-off in the second round of partial municipal elections throughout
Italy also confirmed the strength of the former communist Party of the
Democratic Left (PDS). The Christian Democrats and the Socialists  - the
dominant parties over the past decade  - are the principal losers.
Exit polls and partial counting of votes showed that the Lombard League's
candidate, Mr Marco Formentini, scored a clear victory in the northern
industrial city of Milan.
Mr Formentini notched up about 55-57 per cent of the vote in the second
round. In the earlier round, on June 6, he had won nearly 39 per cent of the
vote and polls during the past week consistently put him ahead.
Nevertheless, his opponent in the run-off, Mr Nando Dalla Chiesa, had put up
a strong showing backed by a leftist alliance headed by the PDS.
'The game is over,' said Mr Umberto Bossi, the League's rough-and-tumble
leader. 'What happened today is a strong signal that the country wants
change. . . . If the League wins, change wins.'
The League's victory in Milan underlines the north's desire for new
political blood and a radical approach to municipal politics in the wake of
widespread corruption scandals.
In the other big northern industrial city of Turin the PDS candidate, Mr
Valentino Castellani, came from behind and easily topped his rival, Mr Diego
Novelli, a former Turin mayor who was supported by a rival group of leftist
parties.
The PDS did well, according to exit polls, in most of the 145 municipalities
where there was a second round contest for mayor. This was the first time
under new laws approved in March that Italy has carried out direct elections
for mayors, who now have the right to choose 60 per cent of municipal
councils and thus ensure stable local government.
The Lombard League has vowed to contest the results of first-round voting in
Turin and a regional appeal court will consider its case next week. This
could lead to the Turin election being annulled.
</TEXT>
