FT  21 JUN 93 / Channel tunnel train is towed powerless to UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIRST Channel tunnel express train to be seen in Britain emerged from
the tunnel mouth at Folkestone yesterday morning  - crawling behind a French
diesel locomotive that had pulled it through the tunnel, writes Richard
Tomkins.
The electrically powered train, built in France, was unable to make its own
way to British shores because the electrical systems in the tunnel have not
yet been switched on.
A total of 38 Eurostar Channel tunnel express trains are being built by GEC
Alsthom, the Anglo-French engineering company, at Pounds 24m apiece. They
will run between London and Paris in three hours when the tunnel opens next
year.
The prototype that arrived yesterday has undergone months of trials in
France and will be tested in England to establish how the trains perform
using the comparatively low-voltage electrical system in use on Network
SouthEast.
Lex, Page 18
