<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Nadir's donation may be returned, says Major
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, ANDREW JACK and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR signalled last night that the Tory party was seriously
considering returning the Pounds 440,000 donated by Mr Asil Nadir.
His comments came amid growing pressure on Mr Michael Mates, the junior
minister linked to Mr Nadir, to resign, threatening a fresh crisis for the
government.
Speaking to journalists on his arrival in Copenhagen for the European
Community summit, the prime minister appeared to suggest that the failure by
the fugitive businessman to declare the donations in company accounts could
be sufficient reason for their return.
In an attempt to defuse the mounting furore, Mr Major reinforced Tory
officials' pledges that the money would be returned to the administrators of
Polly Peck if it was proved to have been dishonestly obtained or remitted by
Mr Nadir.
'Any money that was dishonestly obtained and dishonestly donated to the
Conservative party is not wanted by the Conservative party,' he said. 'If it
is proved to have been dishonestly obtained and dishonestly remitted to us,
then of course we will return it.'
But while stressing his determination that his party should act properly, Mr
Major refused to comment on the future of Mr Mates, the security minister at
the Northern Ireland office.
Support for Mr Mates among Tory MPs fell rapidly at the weekend, and senior
MPs voiced concern that he may have to resign amid the failure of the party
hierarchy to stop continuing controversy over the support given to Mr Nadir
by Conservatives before he fled to northern Cyprus.
Senior Whitehall officials acknowledged that it had been 'unwise' of Mr
Mates to accept the loan of a car from Mr Nadir's public relations advisers.
His future is expected to be raised when the powerful 1922 executive of Tory
backbench MPs meets on Thursday. One member, among the most pessimistic
about Mr Mates's chances of survival, said yesterday: 'I doubt whether he
will last that long.'
A resignation would be a further embarrassment for Mr Major who has only
just recovered from the fallout after Mr Norman Lamont's sacking as
chancellor. Even Tory MPs who are suggesting that Mr Mates may have to go
accept that it would be another example of Mr Major losing a minister after
media pressure.
Mr Mates was unavailable for comment yesterday. However, colleagues were
concerned at the impact of the row which began with revelations that Mr
Mates had raised with the Attorney General Mr Nadir's treatment by the
Serious Fraud Office.
The row over the Nadir donations has triggered calls from within the Tory
party for a wider review of how it sets out its accounts  - demands likely
to be reiterated when the Commons debates the funding of political parties
tomorrow.
Conservative Central Office said yesterday that Sir John Cope, former deputy
chairman and now Treasury minister, had written two years ago to liquidators
of Mr Nadir's business empire setting out the payments the party had
received from him.
However, it was still waiting to be told formally if the donations had been
from 'stolen money'.
Mr David Mellor, former cabinet minister, said one way of dealing with the
issue would be to recognise that the money would never appear a legitimate
donation  - however honourable it seemed at the time  - and send it back.
Administrators at accountants Touche Ross have traced a series of payments
totalling Pounds 365,000 during 1987-90 which were paid through a bank
account in Jersey of Unipac, the northern Cyprus-based packaging
manufacturer within the Polly Peck group.
Touche has also identified several payments totalling at least Pounds 75,000
in the period 1985-87 paid directly with funds from Polly Peck
International, the parent company. None of these political donations was
disclosed in the group accounts, although these details are required by the
law.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, seized on the latest twists in the
financing row to underline his demands that the Conservative party repay
immediately the money contributed by Mr Nadir. Mr Major should explain
publicly the 'very murky' circumstances in which funds were paid to the
Tories, he said.
Tories unsettled, Page 7
Observer, Page 17
</TEXT>
<XX>
