<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 93 / Food and Drink: Sainsbury fizzes with enthusiasm - Britain's
biggest wine merchant now has a range to fit its buying power
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANCIS ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOT BEFORE time, Britain's biggest wine merchant is beginning to show signs
of the sheer enthusiasm for wine that has for several years distinguished
the best of its rivals. More than a decade ago Sainsbury led the
supermarkets' advance into wine merchant territory with a combination of
muscle and confidence that gave it the lion's share of the highly
competitive British wine market.
In recent years, however, Sainsbury's wine department may have kept
shareholders happy by keeping at least a percentage point ahead of Tesco,
its main rival for wine market share. But the famously broad selection
seemed more driven by gaps to be filled and price points to be reached than
inspired by the increasingly dazzling range of plums on offer in the world's
vineyards and cellars. Producers and agents complained that a decision which
took a month chez Safeway, and a minute at Oddbins, could take up to a year
at Sainsbury's.
The company's rivals among multiple retailers may be concerned at its
increasing insistence on exclusive rights to certain lines. Its rivals among
the independent merchants are probably less concerned about Sainsbury's
efforts to overcome the supermarket wine retailer's most serious
shortcoming: lack of expert advice. Sales assistants trained by headphones,
a two-hour audio tape and a workbook are unlikely to be much of a match for
the bevy of wine enthusiasts employed by most decent wine merchants. Nor
does Sainsbury, or any other supermarket, give the independents a run for
their money in the Pounds 5-plus per bottle range.
But the wines that follow all represent bargains from the Sainsbury buying
team, at last reflecting ingenuity as well as heavyweight bargaining (they
seem to have done their own bulk buying from Peter Bright and Hardys of
Australia). It is worth noting, however, that, with the exception of the
Copertino and Green Point, there is no point in keeping these wines; in fact
most are best drunk now, enhanced by the bloom of youth. Some are just
reaching the shelf. Spot the wine with no antipodean connection.
WHITES Chapel Hill Chardonnay 1992 Pounds 2.99. Terrible label, but great
value. Made by a New Zealander in Hungary. Of course. Much more convincing
than Chapel Hill Sauvignon.
The Country Collection Basilicata White Pounds 3.29. Unusually fruity dry
southern Italian, made by the ubiquitous Jacques Lurton of Bordeaux. (Just
Pounds 2.99 at Victoria Wine until the end of June.)
Gyongyos Country White Pounds 3.35. Now for Hugh Ryman (of Bordeaux,
Languedoc, Moldova et al) playing with Semillon grapes in Hungary. Very
lively (and the racy Gyongyos Chardonnay is probably worth the 36p
supplement over the Chapel Hill version).
Chardonnay Delle Tre Venezie Pounds 3.59. New, highly successful, part
barrel-fermented north-eastern Italian.
Sainsbury's Sauvignon Vin De Pays D'oc Pounds 3.59. Better than most
Languedoc answers to Sancerre.
Santa Sara 1992 Pounds 3.95. Oaky, slightly sweet Portuguese white from
Australian Peter Bright.
Chais Beaumiere Sauvignon 1992 Pounds 3.99. Much better than most Languedoc
answers to Sancerre, and possibly the best wine yet from the French outpost
of Hardys of Australia (although their quarter bottles of Merlot 1991
continue to shock British Airways customers with their quality).
Denbies Estate 1991 Pounds 3.99. Well-made lively dry white. Full, round and
fruity. Unapologetically English.
Viognier 1992 Pounds 4.49. Scented, pale version of Condrieu from the
Ardeche co-op.
Moondah Brook Chenin Blanc 1992. Pounds 4.99 Sainsbury's most interesting
Australian wine (as opposed to wine-maker). Oak and lime, but nothing like
after-shave.
REDS Do Campo Tinto Pounds 2.99. Good lively Portuguese red from Peter
Bright, whose Argentinian red Malbec/Cabernet and, especially, white
Torrontes at Pounds 2.99 should be the bargains of August when they arrive.
La Mancha 1992 Castillo de Alhambra Pounds 2.99. More concentrated Spanish
red than previous vintages.
Copertino Riserva 1989 Pounds 3.95. Heady southern Italian, a prime
candidate for cellaring.
Cavas de Weinert 1985 Pounds 6.99. Full, sweet, viscous and a real mouthful.
Special.
OTHERS Jeanmaire 1988 Champagne Pounds 9.95. Special offer. Silly price.
Respectable quality.
Green Point 1990 Pounds 9.95. Australian fizz from Moet &amp; Chandon; every bit
as good as the above.
Nagyrede Cabernet Sauvignon Rose 1992 Pounds 2.99. Pretty, very pale, dry
and scented.
Bouvier Trockenbeerenauslese 1989 Pounds 5.85 (half). Rich, curranty
Austrian dessert wine.
</TEXT>
