<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 93 / London Stock Exchange: Futures expiry overshadows trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HEAVY arbitrage dealing between stock index contracts and the underlying
blue chips provided the backcloth yesterday to the close of the two-week
trading account in the UK stock market. The first half of the session
featured the expiry of the June contract on the FT-SE Index and of June
Share Index options.
The September contract on the Footsie then took over the lead, moving to a
strong premium against the underlying cash market. Both futures and equities
appeared to run out of steam towards the close, however, and traders said
the second half of the day had been less exciting. At the day's best, the
Footsie touched 2,887.6, confidently challenging the higher reaches of its
trading range. But this level was reached in the wake of the settlement in
stock index futures, when the market was distorted by heavy basket trading
by the big investment houses; basket trades involve balancing large deals in
the stock index future with a basket of the underlying blue chips.
The market remained firm throughout the day although progress became more
erratic. The final reading put the FT-SE Index at 2,879.4, for a net gain on
the day of 3.7 points. The FT-SE Mid 250 Index gained 2.3 to a new peak of
3,215.8. Over the two-week account, the FT-SE 100 Index has added 1.7 per
cent and the Mid 250 1.3 per cent.
Strategists said that equities were helped by the generally very favourable
reception for UK unemployment and inflation statistics released on the
previous day. These were seen as convincing evidence that the recovery in
the domestic economy is being sustained.
Strong demand for the September futures contract on the Footsie from a
leading Japanese house provided support for confidence in the outlook for UK
equities. Seaq trading volume jumped to 712.5m shares, but was distorted to
some extent by the index basket trading; non-Footsie business dipped to
around 56 per cent of the total. On Thursday, Seaq volume of 555.4m shares
was worth Pounds 1.36bn at retail level, continuing the recent improvement
in customer activity in equities.
Government bonds firmed up behind a steady performance by sterling,
conventional gilts gaining at the longer end of the range. Index-linked
government bonds, their attractions less visible as the latest data
indicates that inflation remains subdued, held steady.
</TEXT>
