<DATE>930619
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 93 / London Stock Exchange: Drugs underperform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, JOEL KIBAZO and CATHY MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The drugs sector made modest progress but nevertheless continued to
underperform the wider market amid suggestions that at least one big US
broking house, rumoured to be Kidder Peabody, had downgraded the
pharmaceuticals sector.
These rumours offset news earlier in the session that the Clinton
administration in the US has postponed its healthcare reforms.
Another bull point for the sector was the market's confidence that Zeneca's
Pounds 1.3bn rights issue had coasted home, despite persistent talk in the
financial press that the issue would encounter substantial difficulties and
had failed to attract sufficient overseas support. Zeneca's rights close on
Monday.
Zeneca 'old' closed a penny harder at 622p on hefty turnover of 4.2m shares,
while the 'new' shares, quoted in fully-paid form, were the same price. ICI
held at 697p.
Fisons, which drops out of the FT-SE 100 index on Monday, nevertheless
proved the best performer in that index over the week. Although 3 1/2 easier
yesterday at 171 1/2 p on heavy turnover of 4.2m shares, the stock was still
16 1/2 higher over the five-day period, reflecting a mixture of takeover
speculation and the official US launch of its anti-asthma drug Tilade.
TSB shares continued to bump up against their all-time high, reached on
Monday, before closing a net 1 1/2 better at 195p. The bank is scheduled to
reveal interim results on Thursday with pre-tax profits expected to come in
at around the Pounds 75m, compared with a Pounds 92m and the market set to
focus on the level of bad debts.
The water stocks included in the FT-SE 100 list, big winners in mid-week
when a number of institutions were said to have been aggressive buyers, fell
sharply following a sustained bout of profit-taking.
Severn Trent, which goes ex-dividend on Monday, fell 13 to 470p after
exceptionally heavy trading of 4.6m. North West lost 10 to 457p and Anglian
9 to 360 1/2 p. Thames eased 7 to 459p.
Dealers reported substantial switching out of the electricity stocks
('recs') and into the Scottish generators, where Hydro featured with a 5
rise to 344p. Scottish Power hardened to 322p on 4.2m traded.
Southern Electricity dropped 11 1/2 to 455 1/2 p, South Wales 10 to 536p and
Midland 8 to 463p.
BT came in for sustained buying interest, the shares closing 5 higher at
428p; the BT3 marketing effort moved into overdrive at the start of the
week. A bear squeeze drove Cable &amp; Wireless up 9 to 748p.
Blick, the electronics group, plunged 43 to 455p after press comment on the
company's accounting procedures. Advisors to Blick insisted, however, that
the changes were in accounting presentation, not accounting policy. Beales
Hunter was another big casualty in the electricals area of the market, the
shares sliding 27 to 265p, after 262p, following the profits warning.
Shares in Asda, the food retailer, saw the largest volume of trading with
some 27.5m changing hands, with an American buyer thought to have bought a
block of 6m traded at 75p. The stock closed up 1 1/2 p at 74p.
The sector also saw business in Kingfisher, the retail conglomerate, said to
be the focus of some big switching activity with a block of 5m shares traded
at 592p, the eventual closing price and 3 better on the day.
Leading discount food retailer Kwik Save ended its last day in the FTSE 100
index 8 down at 713p, against a background of worries on how the group is
coping in an increasingly tough discount sector.
Brewers looked a lively sector in comparison, with some dealers selling
Guinness, following a presentation by LVMH, the French luxury goods
manufacturer with which the brewer and distiller has a 24 per cent
cross-holding.
Analysts interpreted part of the information as negative about some of the
groups' important markets. The shares closed 11 down at 484p.
Grand Met was the beneficiary of Guinness' misfortune, picking up 7 to close
at 414p.
In food manufacturing, a slow day revived rumours of a bid for United
Biscuits, where the shares closed up 5 at 400p.
The market appreciated reports that British Aerospace is to implement a
reorganisation of its businesses, a move likely to improve its dividends
paying capacity. The shares rose 12 to 413p after trade of 5.2m.
Nervous trading in British Steel ahead of figures on Monday saw the shares
give up 3 1/2 to 98 1/2 p, with US selling, mostly in the final hour of the
session, prompting the slide. Analysts expect the company to report a loss
of Pounds 150 million.
Williams Holdings were favoured by several securities houses, including
Charterhouse Tilney. The shares put on 9 to 318p. Glynwed International
finished 3 ahead at 305p. Carr Kitcat however remained cautious and cut
current year profit expectations by 3.5 million to Pounds 39 million. The
same house weighed in with a savage profit downgraded for APV, reducing the
current year figure by Pounds 9 million to Pounds 14 million. The shares
firmed 1 1/2 to 101.5p. Bid target Securiguard added 8 to 309p amid talk
that its predator Rentokil Group, 3 up at 188p, would soon raise its offer.
Other statistics, Page 12
</TEXT>
