<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 93 / Lawson issues warning to Clarke: Common cause for Thatcher
era adversaries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO ERSTWHILE adversaries of the Thatcher era found common cause yesterday,
advising Mr Kenneth Clarke, the new chancellor, on how to shape his
policies.
And Mr Norman Lamont, chancellor until a few weeks ago, this morning warns
that government policy could be throwing away Britain's chances of economic
recovery.
Lord Lawson and Sir Alan Walters, who as former chancellor and a key
government adviser disagreed openly during the latter years of Mrs (now
Lady) Thatcher's term, yesterday delivered separate warnings over Mr
Clarke's stance at the Treasury.
Lord Lawson denounced any shift towards a 'go for growth' policy. He said
'no sudden burst of growth can produce anything other than a spurt of
inflation'.
Sir Alan launched a direct attack on Mr Clarke. He said on the BBC that Mr
Michael Howard or Mr Michael Portillo should have replaced Mr Norman Lamont
as chancellor. Mr Clarke would spend public money to avoid political
problems.
He added: 'I doubt whether he has the sort of spine needed to control the
books.'
Lord Lawson, as chancellor, once said that there had been an economic
miracle, and pushed the annual rate of growth to 5.1 per cent in early 1988.
Last week he was implicitly blamed for Britain's recent economic
difficulties by Mr Lamont, who claimed in his resignation speech that the
recession of the early 1990s had its origins in the boom of 1988 and 1989.
Lord Lawson, speaking at a seminar arranged by the investment managers
Capital House, said cycles were the normal pattern of economic behaviour.
But he warned of persistent inflationary dangers. 'The dragon of inflation
is asleep but is not dead.' he said. 'It is highly likely to waken up
again.'
Mr Lamont, writing in today's Daily Mail, says government borrowing is 'far
too high' and has to be curbed if Britain is to capitalise on falling
unemployment and stable inflation.
He felt 'pride and pleasure' when he heard that the policies he had put in
place had resulted in this week's fall in unemployment figures.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
